\section*{Introduction}

The three most fundamental problems in the Big Bang theory of cosmology are the flatness problem, the horizon problem and the magnetic monopole problem. In 1980s inflation was proposed\cite{Inflation} to solve them. 
The predictions of inflation paradigm are consistent with observational facts, such as the the highly isotropic Cosmic Microwave Background Radiation (CMBR),  
and the scale invariance of primordial density perturbations attributed to the quantum fluctuations of the inflaton field at the end of inflation\cite{Mukhanov:1990me}. Inflation, however, is not free of problems. For instance, the initial singularity does not disappear but is  delayed\cite{Borde:1993xh}.

Building on the success of inflation models, 
cosmologists have been searching for alternative scenarios  
that also address the problem of the cosmic singularity. 
In 1993 a GR-compatible solution utilising a nonsingular bounce was proposed shortly after the first observation of current expansion\cite{93Solve}. 
At the same time, string theorists attempted to implement a nonsingular bounce in dilaton gravity, leading to the pre-big bang (PBB) scenario within string theory framework\cite{PBB}. And many string inflation models as reviewed by Linde\cite{Linde:2009zz}, and by Tye\cite{HenryTye:2006uv}.

Bounce universe has a long history, dated back to Einstein, and many models\cite{reviews} by now.  A period of contraction is postulated to happen before the period of expansion resulting our current observable universe. The possibility of generating a spectrum of primordial perturbations with an apparent scale invariance during a phase of matter-dominated contraction was pointed out in 1998 by Wands~\cite{Wands:1998yp} (see also~\cite{Finelli:2001sr}) the idea of bounce universe crystallised much later.

For instance, a cyclic/bounce  model in a conventional 
4-dimensional effective field theory can generate a bounce to solve the singularity problem\cite{early-bounce}. 
The famous Ekpyrotic models~\cite{Khoury:2001wf} made use of the D-brane dynamics to engineer a hot big bang. 
There are also a variety of string (gas) bounce models~\cite{string-bounce}.
Outstanding difficulties exist on the way to obtaining ekpyrotic and string bounce models from string theory~\cite{Polchinski:2005qi} 
from first principles.
``Matter bounce'' bounce models driven by ghost condensation were proposed to avoid ghosts in the perturbation spectrum of states\cite{matterbounce}; a bounce model in N=1 super gravity was proposed to get rid of ghost excitations\cite{Koehn:2013upa} and to prove that nonsingular bounces were viable in supergravity. 
 ``G-Bounce'' models  generate non-singularity inflationary cosmos with a Galileon field~\cite{Gbounce}, while Lee-Wick produces  a bounce by the Lee-Wick radiation with an apparent scale invariance in the  perturbation spectrum\cite{LWradiation}.
A bounce solution was also found in the universe dominated by the Quintom matter\cite{Quintom}. Last but not the least,  making use of Loop Quantum Gravity one can generate bounce universe models. See, for example~\cite{LQGbounce} and references therein, and~\cite{Ashtekar:2011ni} for a status report. 

\section{The Single Bounce Criteria}

In a string model with  the  coupled scalar  and tachyon fields--the CSTB model--a bouncing universe happens naturally with a generic set of parameters. 

In an effective field theory description, a D-$\mathrm{\bar{D}}$3-brane pair is described by the open string tachyon field action~\cite{Sen:2004nf},
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{singleaction}
{\mathcal{L}}_T=V_{T}\sqrt{1+M_s^{-4}\partial_{\mu}T\partial^{\mu}T}, 
~ V_{T}=\frac{V_0}{\cosh(\frac{T}{\sqrt{2}M_s})}~~ 
\nonumber
\end{eqnarray}
where $T$, $M_s$, $V_0$ are the tachyon field, the string mass, 
the tension of D-$\mathrm{\bar{D}}$3-brane pair respectively. 
The tachyon potential $V_{T}$ has a maximum at $T=0$ and two minima at $T\rightarrow\pm\infty$. 
We take the background metric as $(-,+,+,+)$, and we also assume that the tachyon field is spatially homogenous.

In D-brane inflation\cite{Dvali:1998pa} the attractive potential of the D-$\bar{D}$ pair takes the following form:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{scalarpotential}
V_{\phi}=\frac{1}{2}m_{\phi}^2\phi^2+V_0-\frac{V_0^2}{4\pi^2\upsilon\phi^4},\qquad \phi\equiv\sqrt{V_0}\,y,
\nonumber
\end{eqnarray}

where $y$ being the distance between the D-$\mathrm{\bar{D}}$3-branes. 
Building on tachyon driven inflation idea introduced independently by 
Sen~\cite{Sen:2003mv} and Gibbons~\cite{Gibbons:2002md} the Coupled Scalar and Tachyon Bounce (CSTB for short) model~\cite{Li:2011nj} introduced a scalar-tachyon coupling term $\lambda\phi^2T^2$, and the tachyon condensation  comes  about naturally after the locked inflation driven by the tension of 
D-$\mathrm{\bar{D}}$3-branes. 
